definition.value: A glycophytoceramide having an alpha-D-galctopyranosyl residue at the O-1 position and a nonanoyl group attached to the nitrogen.
A hydroxypalmitic acid that is palmitic acid substituted by hydroxy group at position 11 (the 11S stereoisomer).
Any metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in prokaryotes, the taxon that include members of domains such as the bacteria and archaea.
A kaempferol O-glucoside that is  kaempferol attached to a beta-D-glucopyranosyl moiety at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.
A kaempferol O-glucoside that is  kaempferol attached to a beta-L-glucopyranosyl moiety at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the amino groups and deprotonation of the phosphate group of any 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-1'-(3'-O-L-lysyl)-sn-glycerol.
A zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the phosphate to the amino group of any 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-1'-(3'-O-L-alanyl)-sn-glycerol.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is kaempferol attached to a beta-D-galactopyranosyl moiety at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.
A kaempferol O-glucoside that is  kaempferol attached to a beta-D-glucopyranosyl moiety at position 4' via a glycosidic linkage.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is kaempferol attached to a beta-D-allopyranosyl moiety at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage.
A kaempferol O-glucoside that is  kaempferol attached to an alpha-L-glucopyranosyl moiety at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage.
A kaempferol O-glucoside that is  kaempferol attached to a beta-D-glucofuranosyl moiety at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage.
Any beta-D-Glc-(1->3')-1,2-diacylglycerol having S-configuration at position 2 on the glucose moiety.
Any dinucleotide where the two components are connected via a (2'->5')-phosphodiester linkage.
A (2'->5')-dinucleotide in which the two nucleoside components connected by the (2'->5')-phosphodiester linkage are adenosine.
A kaempferol O-glucoside that is kaempferol attached to a beta-D-glucopyranosyl moiety at position 5 via a glycosidic linkage.
An oligonucleotide comprised of three adenosine components connected by (3'->5')-phosphodiester linkages.
An oligonucleotide comprised of five adenosine residues connected by 2'->5' phosphodiester linkages and with a triphosphate group at the 5' terminus.
A kaempferol O-glucoside that is kaempferol attached to a beta-L-glucopyranosyl moiety at position 5 via a glycosidic linkage.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is an O-glucuronidated derivative of myricetin.
A myricetin O-glucuronide that is myricetin with a beta-D-glucosiduronic acid residue attached at the 3-position.
A myricetin O-glucuronide that is myricetin with a beta-D-glucosiduronic acid residue attached at the 5-position.
A myricetin O-glucuronide that is myricetin with a beta-D-glucosiduronic acid residue attached at the 7-position.

A 1,4-benzodiazepinone that is 1,3-dihydro-2H-1,4-benzodiazepin-2-one which is substituted at positions 5 and 7 by phenyl and nitro groups, respectively. It is used as a hypnotic for the short-term management of insomnia and for the treatment of epileptic spasms in infants (West's syndrome).
Guanosine substituted at the purine 8-position by an acetyl(9H-fluoren-2-yl)amino group.
A rac-1-monoacylglycerol in which the acyl group is palmitoyl.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is an  O-glucosylated derivative of myricetin.
A myricetin O-glucoside that is myricetin with a beta-D-glucosyl residue attached at position 3.
Guanosine substituted at the purine 8-position by a (9H-fluoren-2-yl)amino group.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is myricetin with a beta-D-galactosyl residue attached at position 3.
A myricetin O-glucoside that is myricetin with a beta-D-glucosyl residue attached at position 3'.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is myricetin with a beta-L-galactosyl residue attached at position 3.
An oxoicosatetraenoic acid in which the oxo group is located at position 8 and the four double bonds at position 5, 9, 11 and 14 (the 5Z,9E,11Z,14Z-geoisomer).

A  dihydropyridine that is 1,4-dihydropyridine substituted by methyl groups at positions 2 and 6, a 3-nitrophenyl group at position 4, a ethoxycarbonyl group at position 3 and a methoxycarbonyl group at position 5. It is a calcium-channel blocker used in the treatment of hypertension.
A myricetin O-glucoside that is myricetin with a beta-D-glucosyl residue attached at position 7.
A myricetin O-glucoside that is myricetin with a alpha-L-glucosyl residue attached at position 3.
An epoxy(hydroxy)icosatrienoic acid that is the (8S,9S)-epoxy-(10R)-hydroxy derivative of icosa-(5Z,11Z,14Z)-trienoic acid.
A myricetin O-glucoside that is myricetin with a alpha-D-glucosyl residue attached at position 3.
A 2,3-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which the 2- and 3-acyl groups are both specified as oleoyl.
A trienoic fatty acid consisting of (8Z,11Z,14Z)-icosa-8,11,14-trienoic acid having additional (7R)-hydroxy- and (5S,6S)-epoxy groups.
A myricetin O-glucoside that is myricetin with a alpha-D-glucosyl residue attached at position 3'.
A myricetin O-glucoside that is myricetin with a alpha-D-glucosyl residue attached at position 4'.
A HOME in which the hydroxy group is located at position 10 with the double bond at position 8 (the 8E,10S-isomer).

A single-stranded DNA oligonucleotide comprised of five deoxyadenosine, five deoxycytidine, five thymidine and four deoxyguanidine residues connected by 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages in the sequence CTGCAGAATTCTGGTACCA.
Any octadecenoic acid bearing a single hydroxy substituent.
A hydroperoxy fatty acid that is the (10S)-hydroperoxy derivative of (8E)-octadecenoic acid.

A compound of iron and sulfate in which the ratio of iron(2+) to sulfate ions is 1:1. Various hydrates occur naturally - most commonly the heptahydrate, which loses water to form the tetrahydrate at 57degreeC and the monohydrate at 65degreeC.
(8E,12Z)-10-hydroperoxy-8,12-octadecadienoic acid with S-configuration at C-10.

A hydrate that is the monohydrate form of iron(2+) sulfate. It is obtained from the heptahydrate by heating above 65degreeC. It is used as a source of iron in the treatment of iron-deficiency anaemia (generally in solid-dosage treatments; for liquid-dosage treatments, the heptahydrate is normally used).
